Async alembic environment for landa-agent-service.

Quickstart
----------
- `uv run alembic upgrade head`  → applies all pending migrations.
- `uv run alembic history`        → lists revisions.
- `uv run alembic check`          → autogenerate dry-run (no DB writes).
- `uv run alembic revision --autogenerate -m "<msg>"`  → new migration.

How to register new app models
------------------------------
`env.py` imports `app.config.db.metadata` for autogenerate. When you add a
SQLAlchemy model in (for example) `app.memory.case_store`, ALSO add an import
of that module in `env.py` so its tables attach to `Base.metadata` before
alembic captures `target_metadata`:

    # In alembic/env.py, near the top:
    from app.memory import case_store  # noqa: F401

Without that import, autogenerate will not see the new tables.

LangGraph checkpoint tables
---------------------------
Migration `0001_initial_schema` creates the four LangGraph tables
(`checkpoints`, `checkpoint_blobs`, `checkpoint_writes`,
`checkpoint_migrations`) by delegating to `AsyncPostgresSaver.setup()` rather
than hardcoded DDL. This keeps the schema synchronised with whichever version
of `langgraph-checkpoint-postgres` is installed at deploy time. See the
docstring of `versions/0001_initial_schema.py` for the full rationale.

Threat model notes
------------------
- alembic.ini intentionally contains NO `sqlalchemy.url`. The URL is composed
  from `app.config.settings.PostgresSettings` at runtime so credentials never
  enter version control (T-01-11 mitigation, 01-03-PLAN.md).
- All DDL must use `IF NOT EXISTS` / `IF EXISTS` for idempotency (T-01-13).
- If `langgraph-checkpoint-postgres` is upgraded to a version that ships new
  MIGRATIONS entries, the next `alembic upgrade head` is a no-op — but the
  next call to `AsyncPostgresSaver.setup()` (at lifespan startup) will apply
  the new entries because `setup()` walks the MIGRATIONS list and checks the
  `checkpoint_migrations` table. This is intentional. Document major
  upgrades by adding a new alembic revision that calls `setup()` again so
  the alembic history reflects the change explicitly (T-01-14).
